<DOCNO> XIE20000603.0008 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Final-Status Negotiations Suspended for Three Days </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GAZA, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The Palestinian-Israeli final status
negotiations have been suspended for three days so that both sides
would have the chance to consult with their leaders on the issues
concerned, according to Palestinian sources.
</P>
<P>
This came only two days after the two sides resumed
negotiations, interrupted by a upsurge of violence between
Palestinian demonstrators and Israeli troops, on Thursday at an
undisclosed venue.
</P>
<P>
The sources who preferred anonymity refused to reveal any
details about the talks.
</P>
<P>
During a meeting of the Palestinian leadership late Friday,
Chairman of the Palestinian National Authority Yasser Arafat
emphasized the Palestinian negotiators will not budge an inch on
any of the fixed national rights.
</P>
<P>
He said he will not accept but full implementation of the signed
accords and the relevant international resolutions, particularly U.
N. Security Council resolution 242 which calls for a complete
Israeli withdrawal from all the occupied Palestinian territories.
</P>
<P>
U.S. State Secretary Madeleine Albright is scheduled to arrive
in the region on Monday to brief Arafat on the outcome of the
summit between U.S. President Bill Clinton and Israeli Prime
Minister Ehud Barak in Lisbon, Portugal.
</P>
<P>
She also aims to give a new momentum to the Palestinian-Israeli
negotiations until both sides reach this month a framework
agreement on the final-status issues including Jerusalem, borders,
settlements, water and refugees.
</P>
<P>
Arafat chaired Saturday night a meeting of the Executive
Committee of the Palestinian Liberation Organization (PLO) and the
Palestinian National Council (PNC) to discuss the latest
developments. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000603.0009 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Verification of Israeli Pullout Nears End: Lebanese FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese Prime Minster Salim Hoss
said negotiations between the United Nations and Lebanon on
verifying Israel's withdrawal from south Lebanon have almost
concluded, but some problems still remain, Oriental radio reported.
</P>
<P>
Hoss said the two sides have reached understanding on most
points while experts were still working on three border spots now
under Israeli control but over which Lebanon claims ownership.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that his country will not abandon any of its
territory.
</P>
<P>
U.N. special envoy Terje Roed-Larsen talked with Lebanese
President Emile Lahoud here Friday night after his one-day visit to
Syria where he met with Syrian Foreign Minister Faruk Shareh, whose
country is the main power broker in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Larsen has in recent weeks been shuttling among Lebanon, Syria
and Israel on issues relating to the verification of Israel's May
24 withdrawal from south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Local radios said the U.N. Security Council will hold meeting
next Tuesday after Larsen submits his report on this issue.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon on Saturday alluded not to link the controversial Shebaa
Farms to the U.N.'s verification of Israeli withdrawal after
Larsen's talks with Shareh, local paper said.
</P>
<P>
Israel said it seized the Shebaa Farms, located on the west side
of Mount Hermon on Lebanese-Syrian border, from Syria in the 1967
Middle East war and that the fate of the farms would be considered
in its peace talks with Damascus when they resume.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon claimed that Syria had bequeathed the 200-square
kilometer fertile farms to it.
</P>
<P>
However, Syria, whose influence in Lebanon is obvious, has
recently suggested that the Shebaa Farms may not be included in
Israel's withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
Demarcation of Lebanese-Israeli borders was a key part in the U.
N. verification of the Israeli withdrawal. Only after verified will
U.N. peace-keepers move to the border region in south Lebanon
vacated by Israeli occupation troops. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
