<DOCNO> XIE20000603.0010 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish PM Urges Ruling Coalition to Keep Confidence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit
said on Saturday that confidence and solidarity atmosphere should
be kept in the three-way coalition government as well as in the
Parliament, the Anatolia News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Ecevit made the remark as tension was brewing in Ankara once
again because of a parliamentary commission's decision to file the
ruling partner Motherland Party (ANAP) leader Mesut Yilmaz to the
Supreme Court over allegations of graft in selling a state-owned
plot.
</P>
<P>
Since three deputies of another ruling partner Nationalist
Movement Party (MHP) joined the opposition deputies in the
commission to make the decision against Yilmaz, the two junior
partners within the coalition soured their relations.
</P>
<P>
Yilmaz, who was accused of abusing his power during his tenure
as the prime minister of Turkey, was reportedly trying hard to
clear his name of all allegations so that he can join the
government.
</P>
<P>
He said that the coalition rests on confidence between the
partners, adding that the MHP deputies who voted against him at the
commission were acting alone, not representing the decision of
their party.
</P>
<P>
He warned, however, that if one partner of the coalition do not
have confidence in each other, it should leave the coalition.
</P>
<P>
Ecevit has tried his best to maintain the coalition in unity and
avoid another government crisis which has been seen in last several
months. "The 57th government has made successes in a short period
of time since it took office last May. Its stability has served
Turkish interests greatly and will continue to do so," he said.
</P>
<P>
The coalition has gone through the failure of a constitutional
amendment to extend former President Suleyman Demirel's term in
office and the success of electing Ahmet Sezer as the new
president.
</P>
<P>
Ecevit said that "most of the public and friendly countries
appreciated our government at present. The main reason is the
confidence and solidarity atmosphere between the coalition
partners."
</P>
<P>
He hoped the coalition, which was composed of his Democratic
Left Party, ANAP and MHP, to keep their reciprocal confidence both
in the government and the parliament. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
