<HEADLINE> Xinhua Mideast News Summary at 2000 GMT, Saturday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GAZA -- The Palestinian-Israeli final status negotiations have
been suspended for three days so that both sides would have the
chance to consult with their leaders on the issues concerned,
according to Palestinian sources.
</P>
<P>
This came only two days after the two sides resumed
negotiations, interrupted by a upsurge of violence between
Palestinian demonstrators and Israeli troops, on Thursday at an
undisclosed venue. (Palestine-Negotiations)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Thirty-nine people went on trial Saturday for a
spillover riot in southern Egypt last January, prior to a main
trial for those charged with killing 20 Christians and one Muslim
in the town of Kosheh in Suhag Governorate.
</P>
<P>
The 39 people are charged with armed robbery, destruction of
public property, illegal gatherings and illegal possesion of
weapons during the riot in Dar al-Salam, which left five people
injured. (Egypt-Riot-Trial)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY -- Foreign ministers of the Gulf Cooperation Council
(GCC) states later Saturday resumed their 75th meeting designed to
discuss some key issues of common concern at regional level.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi issue, GCC-Iranian ties and the Qatari-Bahraini border
dispute top the agenda of the meeting, which opened in the western
Saudi city of Jeddah earlier in the day, according to reports
reaching here. (GCC-FMs-Meeting)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Pharaonic statues and sphinxes as well as Byzantine
coins have been found in the undersea remains of ancient cities off
Egypt's Mediterranean coast, a French undersea explorer said on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The artefacts were found in the underwater vestiges of Herakleum
and Menouthis, off the coast of the town of Canopus, which lie just
east of Alexandria in the Nile Delta, Frank Goddio told a news
conference held in the port city. (Egypt-Undersea Artefacts)
</P>
</TEXT>
