<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs from
the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Turkey's Koc Holding conglomerate has sold 49.18
percent of the shares of its construction subsidiary Garanti Koza
Insaat Sanayi ve Ticaret A.S. to Balfour Beatty of Britain.
</P>
<P>
Koc Holding said in a statement sent to the Istanbul Stock
Exchange that the shares had been sold for 12.4 million U.S.
dollars.
</P>
<P>
It said that 7 million dollars would be paid when the shares are
transferred to the British company and the rest in two years.
</P>
<P>
Following the transfer of shares, both the Turkish and British
sides will hold equal amount of shares and Garanti Koza will be
managed on the basis of co-ownership.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- The U.S.-based Ritz-Carlton Hotel Company and the
Turkish Suzer Group announced in Istanbul Friday that the two
companies had signed an agreement under which the Ritz-Carlton
Istanbul Hotel will open at the end of 2000.
</P>
<P>
Ritz-Carlton Istanbul will be Turkey's first and only five-star
super-deluxe hotel, which will have 244 rooms, most with a view of
the sea, and 21 apartments in addition to 66 double rooms, 21
suites, 156 king-size rooms and one king's suite.
</P>
<P>
Ritz-Carlton Hotel Company has opened hotels in 15 countries and
regions and plans to expand its operations in the United States and
elsewhere around the world.
</P>
<P>
RIYADH -- Representatives from 14 fish factories working in the
member states of the Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC) are expected to
discuss on Monday in the Omani capital Muscat the problems facing
the fish industry, including the taxes imposed by some GCC
countries on imports. They will also discuss the reprocessing of
the fish industry leftovers.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, organized by the Gulf Organization For Industrial
Consultations, will discuss a working paper on the status of the
fish industry in the Gulf region.
</P>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY -- The GCC Aluminum Society was founded on Saturday
during a meeting held in the Qatari capital of Doha.
</P>
<P>
The society, which will be based in the Bahraini capital of
Manama, aims at coordinating GCC industrial development strategies
and mapping out plans on developing the aluminum industry of the
GCC member states, said reports reaching here from Doha.
</P>
<P>
The GCC, a regional political and economic alliance established
in 1981, comprises Bahrain, Kuwait, Oman, Qatar, Saudi Arabia and
the Untied Arab Emirates. 
</P>
</TEXT>
