<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethiopia Slams Eritrean Military Provocations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopia Saturday accused
Eritrea of military provocations against the country, which, it
said, is meant to demonstrate the continuation of the conflict
despite Ethiopia's declaration that the war was over.
</P>
<P>
Eritrea, in a futile attempt to deny its defeat, is continuing
to insist that the war is not over. To prove its point and to
scuttle the peace talks in Algiers, Eritrea has carried out
serious military provocations on various fronts, the Ethiopian
Foreign Ministry said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
In the last two days, Eritrean troops had been launching
attacks against Ethiopian positions in Burre front, the Ethiopian
Government Spoeksperson' s Office also said Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
Reaffirming that Ethiopias positions was unchanged, despite
efforts by the Eritrean regime to rekindle the flames of war, the
Ethiopian Foreign Ministry reiterated that Ethiopia considers the
war over, and that what is now required is the reaching of a
settlement in Algiers under the auspices of the Organization of
African Unity.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia declared on May 31 that the war was over. The
announcement was made while it claimed to have recovered all
occupied territories from Eritrea, and attained all its military
objects.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia said that it was concentrating on diplomatic efforts
to reach a solution to the crisis between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The belligerent Ethiopia and Eritrea began a new round of
proximity talks in Algiers, Algeria, convened by the OAU
Chairman, President Abdelaziz Bouteflicka of Algeria. 
</P>
</TEXT>
