<HEADLINE> Nigerian Labor Organization Calls for Strike Against Petrol Price Hike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The Nigeria Labor Congress (NLC)
Saturday Called upon its members and other Nigerian workers to
begin a "seat at home" strike from Thursday June 8, if the federal
government did not rescind the increase petrol price.
</P>
<P>
A communique issued at the end of NLC' s central working
committee meeting held in Lagos, the economic capital of the West
African nation, said that "the decision (of the price hike) was
most insensitive, inconsiderate and punitive to the citizens of
this country, especially the workers and masses."
</P>
<P>
The largest labor organization said it had no option than act,
as it had warned earlier. It recalled its past statement that
"should government unilaterally increase petroleum products, labor
will resist with all the powers at its disposal."
</P>
<P>
Nigerian government on last Thursday rose the country's petrol
price by 50 percent to 30 naira from 20 (100 naira equals about
one U. S. dollar) per liter.
</P>
<P>
The decision had met with mixed reactions in the Africa's
largest oil producing country. People in the business sector
generally welcomed the move despite the costs added to their
operation, saying it is inevitable to reduce the large amount of
money spent on subsidizing for a low petrol price. 
</P>
</TEXT>
