<HEADLINE> Jordan Expects 3 Percent Growth in 2000: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Jordan will achieve a 3-percent
economic growth in 2000, significant for the country plagued by a
decade-old recession, thanks to the economic reforms adopted by the
government, Minister of Finance Michel Marto said here Saturday.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the state-run Petra news agency, Marto said
the government has won support for most of its reform packages from
the parliament, which he said was crucial for economic growth and
development of the desert kingdom.
</P>
<P>
He said the government was also holding talks with the
International Monetary Fund and other major international lenders
on its reforms and the rescheduling its foreign debts, which
currently stood at a record 7.2 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The government headed by Prime Minister Abdel Rauf Rawabdeh has
taken economic development as its top priority since it was
appointed by King Abdullah Bin Hussein some 15 months ago.
</P>
<P>
It has taken drastic measures to reform the ailing economy,
privatizing key but non-profitable state enterprises, allowing for
greater participation in economy by the private sector and foreign
investors and streamlining bureaucratic procedures of the kingdom.
</P>
<P>
High on the government agenda was to eliminate poverty and check
unemployment, which official figures put at 14 percent as against
26 percent by independent estimates.
</P>
<P>
Nearly one third of the country's 4.5 million population are
living under the poverty line, or 100 dollars a month, according to
official surveys.
</P>
<P>
However, the kingdom registered a 1.5-percent economic growth in
1999, the first sign of recovery of its economy which has remained
sluggish since the 1990 Gulf Crisis triggered by the Iraqi invasion
of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
In the Gulf Crisis, Jordan was isolated by Arab countries, its
most important markets, due to its sympathy with Iraq. 
</P>
</TEXT>
