<HEADLINE> GCC FMs Start Discussion on Key Regional Issues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Foreign ministers of the Gulf
Cooperation Council (GCC) states later Saturday resumed their 75th
meeting designed to discuss some key issues of common concern at
regional level.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi issue, GCC-Iranian ties and the Qatari-Bahraini border
dispute top the agenda of the meeting, which opened in the western
Saudi city of Jeddah earlier in the day, according to reports
reaching here.
</P>
<P>
In his speech to the inaugural session he chaired, Saudi Foreign
Minister Prince Saud Al-Faisal indicated that the GCC states have
not changed their policy towards Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Faisal said the GCC policy towards Iraq is "based on the
necessity that Baghdad abides by the United Nations resolutions
relevant to its 1990 invasion of Kuwait."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he said the Arab states, especially the GCC states --
Bahrain, Kuwait, Oman, Qatar, Saudi Arabia and the United Arab
Emirates -- have always been keen on employing efforts needed to
protect Iraq's unity and independence and on easing the suffering
of the Iraqi people.
</P>
<P>
Speaking about the Bahraini-Qatari border dispute, Faisal voiced
the GCC states' concern about this issue.
</P>
<P>
But he said the GCC is "reassured about the wisdom of the two
countries' leaderships and their keenness on keeping the row away
from whatever is detrimental to GCC solidarity."
</P>
<P>
Both Qatar and Bahrain are claiming sovereignty over several
small but potentially oil-and-gas-rich Gulf islands, which are now
controlled by Manama.
</P>
<P>
On the GCC-Iranian ties, the Saudi foreign minister renewed
calls to Tehran to positively respond to the drive towards strong
ties based on mutual trust and respect for each other's rights.
</P>
<P>
Faisal urged Iran to cooperate with the efforts of a tripartite
GCC committee in charge of mapping out a mechanism for direct talks
between the UAE and Iran to solve their long-standing dispute over
the sovereignty of Gulf islands -- Abu Musa and the Greater and
Lesser Tunbs -- which are now under Tehran's control.
</P>
<P>
Faisal also touched upon the Middle East peace process following
the Israeli withdrawal from south Lebanon late last month.
</P>
<P>
He congratulated Lebanon on the liberation of its land from 22
years of Israeli occupation, which he said would not have been
achieved without the Lebanese resistance.
</P>
<P>
At the same time he blamed the stalemate of the Israeli-Syrian
and Israeli-Palestinian talks on Israel's intransigent policy,
calling on fellow GCC states to intensify efforts to help push
forward the peace process in the Middle East region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
