at service stations, were being caused by a shortage of foreign
currency, as well as problems associated with logistics in
relation to the procurement and delivery of fuel.
</P>
<P>
He also accused Britain of trying to interfere with ships
destined for Beira Port in Mozambique ferrying fuel for Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
"This interference has taken different forms including the
persuasion of suppliers to double the fuel prices," he said.
</P>
<P>
He added that some ships were failing to berth at Beira to
mysterious circumstances such as missing equipment needed to
facilitate docking.
</P>
<P>
He said Zimbabwe continued to receive fuel from the Independent
 Petroleum Group of Kuwait through Beira. The country also
continued to receive supplies from SASOL, ZIMALZAM and ENGEN on
the South African route through Beitbridge by road and rail.
</P>
