<HEADLINE> Malaysia Calls For Lifting Sanctions on Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia calls for lifting the U.N.
sanctions imposed on Iraq since 1990 and hopes to expand its
cooperation with Iraq, the visiting Malaysian Foreign Minister
Hamed Al-Bar said here on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Al-Bar made the remark during his Saturday's meeting with Iraqi
Deputy Prime Minister Tareq Aziz.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, Al-Bar called on the U.N. Security Council to "
take serious and decisive efforts" to end the decade-old sanctions
on Iraq, as they represent "a flagrant violation of human rights,"
he was quoted by the official Iraqi News Agency (INA) as saying.
</P>
<P>
As to the two no-fly zones in northern and southern Iraq imposed
by the U.S. and Britain after the 1991 Gulf War, Al-Bar said they
are "illegal and unjustifiable."
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and British warplanes have been enforcing the no-fly
zones, which are not covered by any U.N. resolution and thus not
recognized by Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
The Malaysian minister meanwhile expressed his country's
keenness to develop relations, especially trade relations with
Iraq, the INA said.
</P>
<P>
For his part, Aziz appreciated Malaysian government's stance of
solidarity with Iraq, saying that Iraq cherishes its friendly ties
with Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
Aziz reiterated Iraq's rejection of the U.N. resolution 1284, as
it does not respond to Iraq's "legitimate demands" and will not
lead to the lifting of sanctions.
</P>
<P>
The Malaysian minister on Saturday also met Iraqi Oil Minister
Amir Muhammad Rashid and Minister of Industry and Minerals Adnan
Abdal-Majid Ahmad, and discussed with them ways to promote the
bilateral cooperation, the INA said.
</P>
<P>
He arrived here Friday to attend meetings of the Joint Iraqi-
Malaysian Trade And Economic Committee. The last round of meetings
were held in Baghdad in 1989. 
</P>
