<HEADLINE> German FM in Cairo on Regional Issues, Bilateral Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 3 (Xinhua) -- German Foreign Minister Joschka
Fischer arrived in Cairo Saturday afternoon for talks on Middle
East issues, especially the Arab-Israeli peace negotiations, with
his Egyptian counterpart.
</P>
<P>
The talks between Amr Moussa and Fischer will tackle the latest
developments of the Middle East peace process in light of Israel's
withdrawal from south Lebanon, Egypt's Middle East News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
Moussa and Fischer will discuss ways to boost the role played by
both Egypt and the European Union (EU) in helping push forward the
peace talks on all tracks, the official news agency said.
</P>
<P>
Israel completed troop withdrawal from south Lebanon on May 24,
ending its 22-year occupation of a border strip. Syria and Israel
have yet to resume talks on the return of the Golan Heights that
Israel captured from Syria in the 1967 Mideast War. The
Palestinians and Israel are negotiating for a final peace accord,
with little progress.
</P>
<P>
Egypt, the first Arab country to sign a peace treaty with Israel
in 1979, is a key mediator between the Arab countries and Israel.
The 15-nation EU, including Germany, wants to play a major part in
helping seek peaceful settlement of the half-century Arab-Israeli
conflict.
</P>
<P>
Moussa and Fischer will also deal with cooperation between the
EU members and Mediterranean countries within the framework of the
Barcelona process, the news agency added.
</P>
<P>
The EU and 12 Mediterranean countries launched the Barcelona
process in 1995 to forge close cooperation in politics, economy,
social issues and security.
</P>
<P>
Also high on the agenda of the talks between the two officials
is bilateral ties. Egypt and Germany maintain close political and
economic relationship. Germany is Egypt's largest trading partner
among the EU members and the second largest aid donor after the
United States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
