<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Women At United Nations  (by Xie Meihua) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 3 (Xinhua) -- As a renewed effort to
achieve the goal of full gender equality, the United Nations has
set it as the highest priority to achieving gender balance at all
levels with the Organization since the Fourth World Conference on
Women in 1995.
</P>
<P>
To this end, U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan has initiated
policies to ensure the full implementation of the Strategic Plan
of Action for the Improvement of the Status of Women in the
Secretariat (1995-2000), introduced in 1994. These policies call
for determined managerial commitment and action, including
specific short-term targets and effective monitoring, in order to
achieve the goal set by the General Assembly of 50/50 gender
equality by the year 2000. Although the target has not yet been
reached, great strides have been made to make this goal a reality.
</P>
<P>
The renewed emphasis on achieving gender balance has paved the
way for the appointment of an unprecedented number of women to
senior positions in the United Nations. The secretary-general
appointed a woman, Louise Frechette of Canada, as deputy secretary-
general, the Secretariat's second highest position.
</P>
<P>
During the 1990s, women assumed in growing numbers top
leadership positions of several Unites Nations programs and
agencies. They include Carol Bellamy, executive director of the
United Nations Children's Fund; Catherine Bertine, executive
director of the World Food Program; Gro Harlem Brundtland,
director-general of the World Health Organization; Sadako Ogata,
United Nations high commissioner for refugees; Mary Robinson,
United Nations high commissioner for human rights; and Nafis Sadik,
executive director of the United Nations Population Fund.
</P>
<P>
Women are also appointed to other top "cabinet positions"
within the United Nations Secretariat. Currently, Angela King
serves as assistant secretary-general and special adviser on
gender issues and the advancement of women; Rafiah Salim is
assistant secretary-general for human resources management; and
Guillian Sorensen serves as assistant secretary-general for
external relations.
</P>
<P>
And as recently as May 1, 2000, the secretary-general decided
to appoint Danuta Hubner of Poland as executive secretary of the
United Nations Economic Commission for Europe. She is the first
women ever to hold the position of executive secretary of a United
Nations regional commission.
</P>
<P>
In addition, three of the other four U.N. regional commissions
have women as deputy secretaries of the Economic and Social
Commission for Western Asia, the Economic and Social Commission
for Asia and the pacific, and the Economic and Social Commission
for Africa respectively.
</P>
<P>
With the surge in appointments of women to policy-making and
leadership positions, the United Nations has achieved a standard
that most of its Member States have yet to attain.
</P>
<P>
The number of women in senior and policy-making positions within
the United Nations Secretariat has increased significantly. Women
now constitute 24.5 percent of those holding positions at the
director level or above. Overall, women accounted for 38.9 percent
of all professional and higher level staff as of March 30, 2000.
</P>
<P>
However, despite the progress in recent years, the United
Nations still clearly falls short of the goal set by the General
Assembly for full gender balance at all levels by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
While the Strategic Plan of Action has generated a significant
increase in the number of women appointed to senior level posts,
it has not had the same positive effect with regard to women's
overall representation at the professional level, which continues
to rise at the rather slow rate of 1.2 percent annually. At the
current rate, the goal will not be reached before the year 2012.
</P>
<P>
The efforts made by the United Nations have changed the face
of the Organization and have been an integral part of the ongoing
efforts to address the existing gender imbalance that goes against
the founding principles of the Organization. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
