<HEADLINE> Turkish Expert Advocates Closer Turko-Chinese Economic Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, June 3 (Xinhua) -- A Turkish foreign policy expert has
in an article called on Turkish entrepreneurs to be more active in
doing business with China.
</P>
<P>
Yuksel Soylemez, veteran diplomat and co-chairman of the Foreign
Policy Institute, said that both China and Turkey are among the big
emerging markets with great economic development potential.
</P>
<P>
The article was carried by the English-language Turkish Daily
News, which devoted a full page to it on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Quoting World Bank statistics, Soylemez said that investment in
infrastructure projects in China is expected to exceed 700 billion
U.S. dollars up to 2004 and beyond. "The construction of the Three
Gorges Dam, expected to cost 24.6 billion dollars and scheduled to
be completed in 2009, is one example among many others," he added.
</P>
<P>
He asked "Why should private Turkish construction companies not
be involved in the infrastructure projects in China?" noting that
Turkish construction firms have completed projects worth nearly 60
billion dollars in the Middle East and Russia.
</P>
<P>
"There are only five small Turkish companies in China involved
in industrial and agricultural production. Their investment is a
mere 16 million dollars," he said.
</P>
<P>
However, "up to now, foreign companies have been determined to
be in the Chinese market whatever the cost is," he noted.
</P>
<P>
During his state visit to Turkey in April, Chinese President
Jiang Zemin invited Turkish entrepreneurs to participate in the
gigantic development scheme of Western China currently underway.
</P>
<P>
Soylemez said tourism is another sphere of closer cooperation
between the two countries, adding that Turkish Airlines (THY),
which runs a route between Turkey and China, expected that Chinese
overseas tourists will take an increased interest in Turkey in the
years to come.
</P>
<P>
Soylemez stated in the article that China is one of the largest
trade economies in the world, and with China's prospected accession
into the World Trade Organization, "its importance is ever
increasing." 
</P>
</TEXT>
