<HEADLINE> 39 Stand Trial for Involvement in Riot in Egypt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Thirty-nine people went on trial
Saturday for a spillover riot in southern Egypt last January, prior
to a main trial for those charged with killing 20 Christians and
one Muslim in the town of Kosheh in Suhag Governorate.
</P>
<P>
The 39 people are charged with armed robbery, destruction of
public property, illegal gatherings and illegal possesion of
weapons during the riot in Dar al-Salam, which left five people
injured.
</P>
<P>
The trial opened at the criminal court in Suhag, capital of the
governorate, which is 400 kilometers south of Cairo, according to
the Middle East News Agency.
</P>
<P>
The riot, in which Coptic Christian businesses were burned and
ransacked, erupted hours after 21 people were killed in the
neighboring town of Kosheh, all but one of them Copts, on the
nights of January 2-3.
</P>
<P>
Ninety-six people who are implicated in the Kosheh massacre,
including 38 charged with murder, are to stand trial on Sunday in
the same Suhag court.
</P>
<P>
As the rest of the world was celebrating the turn of the
millennium, trouble broke out on December 31 in the mainly
Christian town of Kosheh, sparked by a financial quarrel between a
Muslim and a Coptic merchant over a piece of cloth.
</P>
<P>
Twenty-one people were killed, 44 others injured in the Kosheh
riot which spread to Dar al-Salam on the back of rumors that Copts
working at Kosheh water plant had poisoned the water supply to kill
Muslims. 
</P>
</TEXT>
