<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Sends More Troops to Embattled Jaffna  Peninsula </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka has sent another 4,000
soldiers to defend the northern Jaffna peninsula where some 30,000
troops have been battling separatist Tamil Tiger rebels, a senior
government official said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Minister of Defense General Anuruddha Ratwatte said the
reinforcements were already on their way to Jaffna via the north-
eastern port of Trincomalee.
</P>
<P>
"This is a very critical period, a very decisive moment,"
Ratwatte said in a phone-in program over state radio.
</P>
<P>
He said the military situation in Jaffna was still critical,
but with an improvement in troop morale, reinforcements and new
weapons, they were able to defend Jaffna.
</P>
<P>
The Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE) rebels, fighting
for a separate state for minority Tamils in Sri Lanka's north and
east parts since 1983, mounted a ferocious offensive in recent
weeks in a bid to retake their former stronghold of Jaffna.
</P>
<P>
With recent spectacular military gains, the LTTE rebels began
pushing towards Jaffna, raising concern for the safety of 30,000
government soldiers and half a million civilians in the region.
</P>
<P>
However, Ratwatte said the military had stopped retreating and
had begun a counter-offensive against the LTTE, as the political
leadership was determined to defend Jaffna.
</P>
<P>
He said a large number of deserters were rejoining as the
military was gaining the upper hand.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this week, Ratwatte said after a 12-day trip to Jaffna
a shake-up of Sri Lanka's field commanders and new weapons boosted
morale and reversed the "withdrawal syndrome" of troops defending
Jaffna. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
