<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Forces Retake Strategic Position in S. Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 3 (Xinhua) -- U.N. peacekeepers in Sierra Leone
have retaken a strategic road junction after battling with rebels
of the Revolutionary United Front (RUF).
</P>
<P>
The RUF fighters on Friday fired rocket-propelled grenades at
an Indian battalion of some 400 troops, but inflicted no
casualties, reports reaching here Saturday from Freetown quoted
U.N. spokesman David Wimhurst as saying.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. soldiers "responded with heavy machine gun fire and
have reoccupied Rogberi -- which is a very important position for
us -- and they have dug in defensively," Wimhurst said.
</P>
<P>
"Our presence there will certainly stabilize the area", he
added.
</P>
<P>
U.N. troops withdrew from Rogberi early last month after the
RUF took hundreds of U.N. hostages and advanced towards the
capital Freetown.
</P>
<P>
Rogberi Junction lies some 18 kilometers west of the town of
Lunsar on the road to the rebel controlled diamond-mining areas in
the east of the country.
</P>
<P>
The pro-government forces withdrew on Wednesday from Lunsar
after eight- hour fighting with the rebels. Following their first
major setback, they, backed by the U.N. forces, launched a
counter-offensive. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
