<DOCNO> XIE20000603.0059 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethiopia Launches Attack on Assab Front: Eritrea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The Ethiopia forces launched an
all-out attack on the new Assab front at 3:30 am Saturday,
Eritrean Foreign Affairs Ministry said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The statement reaching here Saturday morning said that intense
fighting was continuing.
</P>
<P>
It said "the Eritrean frontline at Assab is a new frontline set
at 37 kilometers west of the Red Sea port city and the original
frontline was at Burrie, 71 kilometers from the port city."
</P>
<P>
Eritrea redeployed to this new position is response to the
express appeal of Abdelaziz Bouteflike, chairman of the
Organization of African Unity (OAU) and Algerian President, the
Foreign Ministry said.
</P>
<P>
"Eritrea completed redeployment to the new frontline last Sunday
which was verified by the diplomatic community in Eritrea and the
international press which visited the area on May 30," the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
"Ethiopia's offensive on the Assab front deep into Eritrean
sovereign territory demonstrates, once again, that the war it has
launched has nothing to do with a border conflict," the statement
said, adding "this is purely a war of invasion."
</P>
<P>
The Eritrean government called upon the international community
and the OAU and its partners to condemn Ethiopia's war of invasion
and the offensive that it had launched on the Assab front.
</P>
<P>
Eritrea Friday also accused Ethiopia of carrying out a bombing
raid on the city water depot in Assab on Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia launched a massive offensive along the common border
three weeks ago, advancing deep inside Eritrea.
</P>
<P>
The two Horn of Africa countries are now involved in peace
talks being brokered by the OAU in Algeria. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
