<DOCNO> XIE20000603.0060 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Staffers Held Hostage in Georgia, One Released </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, June 3 (Xinhua) -- A group of U.N. military observers
missing since Thursday has been confirmed as being kidnapped in
Georgia's breakaway Abkhazia region, the Interfax news agency
reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
One of the observers has been released, Interfax said, citing
Veselin Kostov, political secretary of the U.N. military
observers' mission in the former Soviet republic.
</P>
<P>
The released hostage was identified as Ismet-Zade, an ethnic
Abkhaz with the Yellow Trust mine disposal organization.
</P>
<P>
He said all three remaining hostages, including a female
interpreter, are alive.
</P>
<P>
The unidentified abductors said they would get in touch with
authorities to put their demands, said Kostov.
</P>
<P>
Ethic unrest in the Abkhazia region escalated into armed
conflict in 1992. In September 1993, separatist forces captured
Sokhumi, the regional capital.
</P>
<P>
An estimated 7,000 people died in the conflict before a cease-
fire agreement was reached in May 1994 under Russian auspices. A
peacekeeping force of 2,500 troops of the Commonwealth of
Independent States (CIS) was sent to patrol the borders of the
region.
</P>
<P>
In November 1994, the Abkhazian legislature declared the
republic sovereign. In 1996, CIS leaders agreed to impose economic
sanctions against Abkhazia until it willingly returns to Georgia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
