<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Avian Paleontologists (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
by Xinhua Writers Zhu Qi and Yu Zheng
</P>
<P>
BEIJING, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Avian Paleontologist Zhou Zhonghe
today received a gift from one of his American colleagues -- a
blue Indian token of "Dream Catch".
</P>
<P>
Indian legends say that the feathered ornament will help its
owner to catch all his dreams.
</P>
<P>
As China's first curator of bird fossil, Zhou is trying to
unravel the mysteries of the relationship between dinosaursand
birds and the origin of flight.
</P>
<P>
The 35-year-old scientist has also been named as one of China's
100 most outstanding academic leaders in the 21st century chosen
by the Chinese Academy of Sciences (CAS), the state's top
scientific research organ.
</P>
<P>
Together with colleagues at the CAS Institute of Vertebrate
Paleontology and Paleoanthropology (IVPP), Zhou found a huge
reserve of Mesozoic bird fossils in 1990 near Chaoyang, northeast
Liaoning Province.
</P>
<P>
Zhou's discovery of fossilized creatures and missing links in
the evolution of birds has been highly praised by his colleagues.
</P>
<P>
Since then, the young scientist has combined his own dream with
the research of primitive birds.
</P>
<P>
During his studies at the University of Kansas in the United
States, Zhou shared differences of opinion with his teacher
regarding the relationship between dinosaurs and birds. "I don't
like any personal attack, but neither do I like agreeing on
opinions without solid scientific evidence," he said.
</P>
<P>
Zhou spends at least three months a year on fieldwork in the
surrounding areas of Jehol Biota in Liaoning province.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000603.0068 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Avian Paleontologists (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
by Xinhua Writers Zhu Qi and Yu Zheng
</P>
<P>
The authoritative scientific journals "Nature' and "Science"
published four articles co-authored by Zhou, showing the latest
discovery of Jehol Biota, which has been widely regarded as
competing with Solenhofen in Germany where Archaeopteryx fossils
were unearthed.
</P>
<P>
In 1999, the avian paleontologist was invited to give a keynote
speech at an international meeting of the origins and evolution of
birds at Yale University, an important center for paleontology.
</P>
<P>
He was also chosen by the United States National Geographic
Society as among the world's most prestigious scientists.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Miman, CAS academic and chairwoman of the organizing
committee of the Fifth International Meeting of the Society of
Avian Paleontology and Evolution and the Symposium on Jehol Biota,
values Zhou as "a extremely promising paleontologist and a rising
star."
</P>
<P>
When delivering a speech to the international meeting in
Beijing, Zhou expounded his hypothesis that Caudipteryx, a kind of
small dinosaur living some 120 million years ago, could perch on
trees and glide through the air among the trees.
</P>
<P>
He claimed that the find is further evidence supporting the
theory that birds originated from dinosaurs.
</P>
<P>
After obtaining his doctoral degree at University of Kansas,
Zhou came back to work in CAS institute.
</P>
<P>
"I favor the research atmosphere at home," he said, "and I will
never feel lonely here. I'm sure that I can catch all my dreams
in China," Zhou said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
