<HEADLINE> Nigerian Cabinet Reshuffled </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian President Olusegun Obasanjo
has announced a major cabinet reshuffle for the first time since
he came to power last May, with three ministers resigned and nine
swapped positions, said local media here Saturday.
</P>
<P>
According to a statement released in the capital Abuja on
Friday and signed by Secretary to the Government of the Federation
Chief Ufot Ekaette, the three ministers resigned are Minister of
State for Works and Housing Isaiah Balat, Minister of Civil
Service Matters Alhaji Mohammed Bello Kirfi and Minister of
Industry Iyorchia Ayu.
</P>
<P>
Following are the seven ministers swapped their portfolios:
</P>
<P>
Chief Bola Ige of Power and Steel Ministry is now
Attorney-General of the Federation and Minister of Justice; former
Attorney-General Kanu Agabi becomes Minister of Solid Minerals
Development; Kema Chikwe of Ministry of Transport serves as
Minister of Aviation; Olusegun Agagu moves from aviation to power
and steel; Alhaji Musa Gwadabe moves from solid minerals
development to labour and productivity; Alabo Tonye Graham-Douglas
of labor moves to culture and tourism; and Chief Ojo Maduekwe
moves from culture and tourism to transport.
</P>
<P>
Also in the new dispensation, Alhaji Bello Usman becomes
Minister of State for Civil Service Matters in the Presidency
while Bekky K Igweh becomes Minister of State for Women Affairs
and Youth Development.
</P>
<P>
The three new minister to be appointed pending the confirmation
of the Senate are Alhaji Garba Ali Madaki, Stephen Akiga and Isa
Yuguda.
</P>
<P>
The media quoted Ekaette as saying that President Obasanjo
expressed his appreciation of the three relieved ministers for
their past services and wished them every success in their future
endeavour.
</P>
<P>
However, no reason was given for the resignation of the
ministers, said Ekaette, adding that "the redeployment takes
immediate effect" and the process of handing-taking over should be
completed by June 7.
</P>
<P>
In early April this year, Minister of Information Dapo Sarumi
and Minister of African Cooperation and Integration Jerry Gana
swapped their positions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
