<DOCNO> XIE20000603.0086 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> General Zhang Xueliang's 100th Birthday Celebrated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, June 3 (Xinhua) -- A number of activities were held
today in Shenyang, capital of northeast China's Liaoning Province,
to celebrate the 100th birthday of General Zhang Xueliang who now
lives in Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
Born on June 3, 1901 on a horse-drawn carriage in northeast
China's Liaoning Province, General Zhang Xueliang is famous for
his part in the Xi'an Incident in which he and General Yang
Hucheng arrested Chiang Kai-shek, leader of the Kuomintang (KMT),
on December 12, 1936. The incident was eventually settled
peacefully with the efforts of the Communist Party of China (CPC).
</P>
<P>
However, Zhang was imprisoned by Chiang soon after the incident,
and spent decades under house arrest in Taiwan under the KMT while
General Yang was tortured to death in a KMT prison in September
1949.
</P>
<P>
A museum based on the former residence of the 100-year-old
general in this northeast Chinese city attracted a steady stream
of visitors.
</P>
<P>
Many took pictures with General Zhang's portrait carved out of
a black marble by Chifeng Stone Arts and Crafts Company of Inner
Mongolia. The black marble portrait was specially made to mark the
occasion.
</P>
<P>
On display were some 300 pictures and reference materials as
well as more than 100 paintings and calligraphy featuring General
Zhang.
</P>
<P>
A forum was also held by historians and specialists recalling
the general's deeds and his concerns about the reunification of
the motherland. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
