<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Cultural News: Weekly Highlights (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
-- China to Exhibit Dali Paintings
</P>
<P>
The China Art Gallery plans to exhibit the paintings of
Salvador Dali, one of the most influential surrealist artists of
the 20th century, from June 9 to 27.
</P>
<P>
The exhibits feature 20 oil paintings and 38 sketches by the
Spanish artist. Dali is widely regarded as one of the century's
most masterful and prolific painters.
</P>
<P>
-- Museum to Showcase Red Army Slogans
</P>
<P>
The city of Liuyang in central China's Hunan Province is
planning the construction of a museum to house a collection of
slogans used by the Chinese Red Army in the 1920s and 1930s.
</P>
<P>
Liuyang was the main site of the Autumn Harvest Uprising, an
armed uprising led by Mao Zedong in 1927 along the Hunan-Jiangxi
border. The uprising marked the Party's independence as a
revolutionary army.
</P>
<P>
-- Beijing to Protect Its Ancient City
</P>
<P>
Beijing Mayor Liu Qi said on June 2 that construction projects
in the capital have to be blend with the ancient buildings and
architecture in the city.
</P>
<P>
He said that any construction project that does not meet with
preservation requirements will not be given the green light. If
construction goes ahead, advanced technologies should be used to
protect historical relics. The capital city of several dynasties,
Beijing is one of the architectural wonders of the world.
</P>
<P>
-- Third Asia Art Festival Opens in Beijing
</P>
<P>
The Third Asia Art Festival opened Thursday night in Beijing
with music performed by a well-known Indian violinist.
</P>
<P>
The three-month festival, hosted by the Ministry of Culture and
organized by the China Performing Arts Agency, marks the 25th
anniversary of the Sino-Philippine diplomatic ties and the 50th
anniversary of Sino-Indian diplomatic relations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
