<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Cultural News: Weekly Highlights (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The following are the highlights of
cultural news stories Xinhua released from May 27 to June 2:
</P>
<P>
-- National Library Receives Rare Kung Fu Manuscripts
</P>
<P>
Yongxin, head of the Songshan Shaolin Temple in central China's
Henan Province, on May 27 presented a set of rare books on Shaolin
kung fu and medical skills to the National Library of China.
</P>
<P>
The rare martial arts teaching manuals have never before been
let out of the temple. Three years ago, representatives from the
temple, Zhonghua Book Company and other institutes invited experts
of martial arts, medicine and publishing to sort through the
temple's store of kung fu books.
</P>
<P>
-- Northeast China Art Expo Slated for Shenyang
</P>
<P>
The 2000 Northeast China Art Expo will be held from June 15 to
21 in Shenyang, capital of Liaoning Province.
</P>
<P>
Artists, collectors, and visitors from all over China as well
as some twenty foreign countries will attend the expo which will
exhibit, exchange, and trade traditional Chinese paintings, oil
paintings, calligraphy, sculpture, pottery, folk art, curios,
crafts, and tourism souvenirs.
</P>
<P>
-- Yuanmingyuan Antiquities Attract Beijingers
</P>
<P>
Thousands of Beijing residents on May 29 rushed to the Poly Art
Museum for an exhibition of three Chinese national treasures
looted by British and French troops when they invaded Beijing in
1860.
</P>
<P>
The antiques are bronze heads of an ox, a tiger, and a monkey,
three of the 12 animal sculptures in a water clock designed for
the Yuanmingyuan Palace, described as one of the most splendid
gardens in the world. The three pieces were recovered at auctions
in Hong Kong and the Poly Group Corporation of China bought them
for more than 33.17 million Hong Kong dollars.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
