<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerian Police Invasion of Senate President's Home </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian police have forced into
the residence of the Senate President Chuba Okadigbo in the
capital Abuja following the long-running face-off between the
executive and legislative arms of the government, newspapers here
reported on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the police surrounded Okadigbo's home
Friday, but failed to press him to hand out his power.
</P>
<P>
The surprising drama seemed to be one of the peaks of a long-
standing row between President Olusegun Obasanjo and the senate
president.
</P>
<P>
"I have to be dead before you get the mace," Okadigbo was
quoted  as saying in Abuja after the event.
</P>
<P>
But, President Obasanjo has denied any involvement in the
police invasion of the residence of Okadigbo, saying that the
immunity granted the leaders of the National Assembly by the
constitution cannot be questioned.
</P>
<P>
Okadigbo, who is the third most powerful politician in Nigeria
after the president and vice president, said the police withdrew
from his Abuja home after he refused to hand over the mace, which
symbolizes the authority of Nigeria's upper house of the senate.
</P>
<P>
The police action followed a decision on Wednesday by Okadigbo
to adjourn the Senate until July.
</P>
<P>
This prompted some senators and members of the government to
call for his removal.
</P>
<P>
"They told me they had come to collect the mace and that they
were acting on orders from the Inspector General of Police,"
Okadigbo explained.
</P>
<P>
President Obasanjo has repeatedly criticized the senate for
being responsible for the constant delays in passing vital bills,
such as the anti-corruption bill or the 2000 federal budget into
laws.
</P>
<P>
The senators on the other hand accuse President Obasanjo of
acting unilaterally in issues that require the approval of the
senate.
</P>
<P>
The tussle between the executive and the legislature came to a
head on May 29, when Okadigbo and other senators boycotted
celebrations marking the first anniversary of the new civilian
government after 15 years of military rule.
</P>
<P>
The day was declared a public holiday that was celebrated as
Democracy Day, but the senate leader said President Obasanjo did
not have the right to declare the day a national holiday.
</P>
<P>
President Obasanjo has been making appeals to Nigerians
recently, calling on them to put pressure on their lawmakers in
order to speed up the government's reform of state institutions.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the government of Nigeria has granted pardon to a
former speaker of the Lower House of the Senate, Ibrahim Salisu
Buhari, who was convicted last year of perjury and forgery,
according to reports of Nigerian newspapers on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The government said on Thursday the presidential pardon to
Buhari was decided in Abuja at a meeting of the Council of State
which includes governors of all Nigeria's states.
</P>
<P>
Presidential pardons were also announced for 14 other people,
including four journalists and two human rights activists
convicted of involvement in a failed 1995 coup plot. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
