<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs from
the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Turkey and Greece opened their first joint venture in
information technology, reported Turkish Daily News on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The company Despil A.S. was established by Photios Gilliadis,
President of Despac Hellas, a Greek subsidiary of the Dutch company
Despac, and Erol Bilecik, former owner of Despac Turkiye, a Turkish
subsidiary of the same company.
</P>
<P>
Turkish and Greek partners will have equal stakes in the
company. The joint venture has an 8.75-million-U.S.-dollar capital
investment.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- Oman saw its oil export revenue stand at 483.9
million rials (1.26 billion U.S. dollars) in the first two months
of this year, up by 150 percent from 193.5 million rials (503.1
million dollars)in the same period of 1999.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, non-oil exports rose by 35.6 percent to 43.8 million
rials (113.88 million dollars) during the two-month period from 32.
3 million rials (83.98 million dollars) in the same period of last
year.
</P>
<P>
Oman produced 54.2 million barrels of crude oil from January to
February this year, up by 3.3 percent from 52.4 million barrels in
the first two months of last year, Oman News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- The second Turkish Aegean Coasts and Greek Aegean
Islands Economic Summit was held in Izmir, Turkey's third largest
city, Friday to boost economic cooperation between the two Aegean
neighbors, reported Turkish Daily News on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Since a business delegation from Izmir visited Athens last
month, the trade volume between the two countries rocketed to 700
million U.S. dollars in a month, said the report.
</P>
<P>
Ekrem Demirtas, chairman of the Izmir Chamber of Commerce,
called on the participants to do their utmost to reach the target
of 4 billion dollars in bilateral trade this year.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- Oman Air was currently studying the possibility of
operating cargo flights linking Salalah with the United Arab
Emirates (UAE) and the Indian Subcontinent, reported Dubai-based
Gulf News daily Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The service would facilitate Oman's import and export and
stimulate transit traffic and boost economic activities at Salalah
port, said Director-General of Oman Air Abdul Rahman al-Busaidi.
</P>
<P>
Negotiations on the service is underway with the Salalah Ports
Services Company, he said.
</P>
<P>
Oman Air would operate daily direct flights between Salalah and
Dubai Emirate of UAE from October, in order to facilitate
passengers movement and attract foreign tourists. 
</P>
</TEXT>
