<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila Remains Hopeful of Basilan Hostages Release </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government said
Saturday that it can still ensure the safe release of the eight
remaining hostages held by the extremist Abu Sayyaf in Basilan.
</P>
<P>
Robert Aventajado, chairman of the presidential flagship
projects committee, said in a radio interview here that the
government will do what it can to secure the hostages' freedom.
</P>
<P>
"There is still hope. I intend to deal honestly with the
hostage takers," said Aventajado, the chief government negotiator
tasked to secure the safe release of 21 hostages, mostly
foreigners, being held by the Abu Sayyaf in the southern province
of Sulu.
</P>
<P>
Aventajado said he is now verifying whether the Basilan
hostages are in the hands of an Abu Sayyaf faction that offered to
turn over the hostages to him. The hostage takers in Basilan
reportedly have sent feelers that they want to turn over their
captives to Aventajado.
</P>
<P>
Citing reports reaching his office, Aventajado said the Abu
Sayyaf is still holding eight hostages in Basilan, including two
teachers, five students, and the son of a soldier who was killed
in a clash with the rebels.
</P>
<P>
The students and teachers were among scores of hostages taken
by the Abu Sayyaf on March 20.
</P>
<P>
Government troops started rescue operations on April 22,
resulting in the safe recovery of 17 hostages. The Abu Sayyaf
killed six of the hostages, including a priest.
</P>
<P>
Aventajado said the turnover of the remaining hostages was to
take place earlier this week, but it did not push through after
this was leaked in the media.
</P>
<P>
Reiterating the government's no-ransom policy, Aventajado ruled
out any payment for the release of the Basilan hostages. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
