<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan Allows Internet Merchant Accounts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 3 (Xinhua) -- In a landmark decision, State
Bank of Pakistan (SBP) has authorized all banks of the country to
open Internet Merchant Accounts which shall enable online business
transactions.
</P>
<P>
According to informed sources, this decision was made at a
meeting of SBP Governor Ishrat Hussain with federal Science and
Technology Minister Atta ur Rahman.
</P>
<P>
At present around 3,000 applications are pending with Pakistani
banks for internet merchant accounts and this facility will allow
local exporters to tap the global market through the net.
</P>
<P>
So far Pakistani exporters have been paying heavy discounts on
internet-based transactions as the payments made for Pakistani
goods and services through credit cards are held outside the
country.
</P>
<P>
In another decision, SBP has approved an expedited shipment
plan for orders received through the websites.
</P>
<P>
Under the plan, a single internet order with a value of up to
500 dollars will be allowed without the formality of filing in an
E-form and would be treated as a courier dispatch.
</P>
<P>
This would reduce the custom clearance time and the customs
department is being asked to give same day priority clearance to
such internet export orders, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan is lagging behind in net-based trade and banking
activity and other Business-to-Business (B2B) and Business-to-
Customer (B2C) forms of E-commerce.
</P>
<P>
Only a small number of Pakistani companies have entered the B2C
arena and even fewer have developed websites and booked orders on
the internet. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000603.0102 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania, Burundi Agree to Curb Smuggling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania and Burundi have
agreed to exchange information to crack down smuggling through the
Lake Tanganyika and other illegal entry points, local newspapers
reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
According to a memorandum of understanding signed here on
Thursday, customs departments of the two countries will carry out
joint patrols on the Lake Tanganyika and inform each other of ways
that smugglers use to transport goods.
</P>
<P>
The memorandum, signed by Burundian Director for Customs and
Excise Pierre Claver Gahungu and Tanzanian Commissioner of Customs
and Excise Department George Lauwo, identifies smuggled high duty
transit goods as oil, cigarettes, textiles, electronics, sugar,
garments, wines, beer and spirits.
</P>
<P>
"Prior to shipment of high duty transit goods to Burundi, the
customs administration in Burundi should confirm to its
counterpart in Tanzania the list of importers. The arrival of the
goods at intended destinations should also be confirmed," the
memorandum said.
</P>
<P>
The memorandum said that the customs administration in Burundi
should furnish its Tanzanian counterpart orders of fuel made
through letters of credit.
</P>
<P>
"To make the transit corridor competitive, the customs
administration in Tanzania should waive the transit bond security.
Briefcase customs agents should not be allowed to handle transit
cargo," the memorandum said.
</P>
<P>
The two neighboring states also intended to curb illicit drug
trafficking and enforce existing customs laws.
</P>
<P>
Burundian authorities would be required to submit a list of
customs agents authorized to handle cargo destined for Burundi.
And designate entry points of its transit goods through Tanzania
should also be identified.
</P>
<P>
To curb dumping and smuggling of transit petroleum products in
Tanzania, the two departments have agreed that Burundi Customs
Department will furnish the Tanzania Revenue Authority a list of
all oil marketing companies in Burundi.
</P>
<P>
In another development, the Burundi Defense Forces have
released eight Tanzanian fishermen and one from the Democratic
Republic of the Congo who were abducted on the Lake Tanganyika
last Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
Tanzanian Chief of Defense Forces General Robert Mboma Friday
told a local newspaper, The Guardian, that the fishermen were
released following his communication with the Bujumbura Defense
Forces top administration.
</P>
<P>
Mboma said that he has directed his subordinates in western
Kigoma Region to double check whether the remaining three
fishermen are not Tanzanians whom the Burundian authorities
identified as Burundian nationals.
</P>
<P>
Last Thursday, General Mboma said the Burundian army was
holding hostage 12 Tanzanian fishermen because it suspected they
were rebels from the National Council for Defence of
Democracy-Forces for Defence of Democracy (CNDD-FDD). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
