<DOCNO> XIE20000603.0103 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Africa Accounts for One Percent of World's GDP </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Africa accounts for barely 1
percent of global gross domestic product (GDP) and only about 2
percent of world trade, according to a book "Can Africa Claim the
21st Century".
</P>
<P>
The book, launched in Kenya's capital Nairobi Friday, says that
Africa's share of global manufactured exports is almost zero and
over the past 30 years Africa has lost market share in global
trade, even in traditional primary goods.
</P>
<P>
The book is a joint product of the World Bank, the African
Development Bank and the U.N. Economic Commission for Africa,
among others.
</P>
<P>
If Africa had maintained its share of world trade from the late
1960s, its exports and income would be some 70 billion U.S.
dollars today, the book says.
</P>
<P>
It says African economies have already begun to diversify and
make themselves more attractive for private sector investments,
adding that the challenge is to sustain the momentum of
diversification in some cases and to jump-start it in others.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the launch, Kenyan Vice-President George Saitoti
said that Africa should stay on the reform path if it is to emerge
from poverty. 
</P>
</TEXT>
