<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Coming Nigeria's Petroleum Price Rise Evokes Mixed Response </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
By Song Li
</P>
<P>
LAGOS, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian government's decision to
raise the price of petroleum by 50 percent to 30 naira per liter
has met with mixed reactions in Africa's largest oil producing
country.
</P>
<P>
After hearing the news announced by the state-owned Nigerian
National Petroleum Corporation (NNPC) on Thursday, motorists in
Lagos, the largest city in the country, rushed to local petroleum
filling stations to buy petroleum at the original price of 20
naira (one U.S. dollar equivalent to 100 naira) per liter, which
had remained unchanged since December 1998.
</P>
<P>
According to the decision, which was approved by President
Olusegun Obasanjo, a liter of Premium Motor Spirit (PMS) now goes
up for 30 naira and may see further rising-ups in the future.
</P>
<P>
People in the business sector generally welcomed the move
despite the costs added to their operation.
</P>
<P>
"This is an achievement in a democratic government. It is
commendable. What military governments were afraid to do, a
democratic government has been able to do it," said Abba Gana,
president of the Major Marketers Association of Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
He said price increase is the only option to avoid sinking huge
amounts of money into subsidizing fuel products imported into the
country.
</P>
<P>
According to NNPC group manager Gaius Obaseki, the corporation
spent 19. 4 billion naira (194 million U.S. dollars) in
maintaining low petroleum product price only in the first three
months of this year, and could spend even more in the second
quarter.
</P>
<P>
The latest increases notwithstanding, the corporation would
still not be able to recover its production cost, he said.
</P>
<P>
However, local sources told Xinhua that the decision instantly
led to an increase of over 100 percent in transport fares in many
parts of the country and invited violent criticisms from the
Nigeria Labor Congress, which even threatened a resistance to the
hike.
</P>
<P>
The Petroleum Committee of the House of Representatives also
"regretted" the decision, saying it would further lower the life
quality of the country's huge population living in poverty.
</P>
<P>
For the poor, the price hike seems a rather unpopular policy at
the time being, especially when the country's poor has yet to see
the economic benefits promised by the first civil administration
after more than a decade of military misrule.
</P>
<P>
"The newly adopted 5,500 naira (55 dollars) minimum wage (up
from a former 3,000 naira), which we had just finished cheering
for, is largely put on sales due to the price hike," a Lagos
resident complained in an interview.
</P>
<P>
His words further illustrated the dilemma the Obasanjo
administration is involved in: to raise the living standard of the
people and to cure the ailing economy at the same time -- but the
problem is that the two are often at odds.
</P>
<P>
Since its inauguration last May, the Obasanjo administration
has repeatedly vowed to deregulate the petroleum industry with a
final aim to allow marketers to set the prices to a level which
will make their operation profitable.
</P>
<P>
The wide-spread non-profitability in the country's economy,
which might be tolerated when the country was rich in the 1970s
and early 1980s, seemed to have run into a dead end after the
mid-1980s when the country's income dwindled largely due to the
mismanagement of corruptive military leaders.
</P>
<P>
The Obasanjo administration needs to free large sums of money
from subsidization to materialize its campaign promises: to free
the economy from total reliance upon the oil sector, achieve
universal education and mend dilapidating infrastructures.
</P>
<P>
Besides, the government also wants to use the price hike to
fight ramping smuggling of the comparable cheap petroleum products
from the country to its neighbors and avoid heavy losses for the
country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
