<HEADLINE> Highlights of Diplomatic News Weekly (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Chinese President Jiang Zemin and Indian President Kocheril
Raman Narayanan Monday agreed to work for an early and proper
settlement of the border issue between the world's two most
populous countries.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said in talks with the Indian president that it will take
time and patience on the part of both sides to settle the border
issue left over from the past. He said China has always taken a
positive approach toward the settlement of this issue.
</P>
<P>
President Jiang also made a four-point proposal for the
development of China-India relations.
</P>
<P>
Chinese top legislator Li Peng, Premier Zhu Rongji and Chairman
of the National Committee of the Chinese People's Political
Consultative Conference Li Ruihuan also met with President
Narayanan on separate occasions.
</P>
<P>
 President Jiang Meets Leaders of Japanese
</P>
<P>
 Coalition Parties
</P>
<P>
President Jiang Zemin expressed the hope Tuesday that China and
Japan should adopt a highly responsible attitude toward the coming
generations and the peace and development of mankind as they push
forward bilateral relations to a new height.
</P>
<P>
Jiang's remarks came in a meeting with the secretaries-general
of the three coalition parties of the Japanese government.
</P>
<P>
Hiromu Nonaka of the Liberal Democratic Party, Tetsuzo
Fuyushiba of the New Komeito Party, and Takeshi Noda of the New
Conservative Party arrived in China on Monday for a two-day visit.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji told the Japanese delegation that
Japan should honor the one China principle, properly handle the
Taiwan issue, and open up the future of Sino-Japanese friendly
relations in the spirit of drawing on lessons from history.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese premier said he would like to pay an official
goodwill visit to Japan in October at its invitation, in order to
boost Sino-Japanese friendship and cooperation.
</P>
