<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Approves Loan to Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank approved a financial
package of 230 million U.S. dollars for a 15-year term to help
implement the 360-megawatt Haripur Power Project, The Bangladesh
Observer reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The International Finance Corporation (IFC), the World Bank's
lending affiliate for the private sector, approved debt financing
of 54.1 million dollars for the power project and exposure for 115
million dollars of interest rate swaps as well as a 60.9-million-
dollar partial risk guarantee by the International Development
Association(IDA), the World Bank's concessionary window.
</P>
<P>
Both the IFC and the IDA had played a key role in catalyzing
the important commercial financial package for a term of 15 years,
the first ever long-term financing of its kind for Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
Vivek Talvadkar of the IFC said the Haripur project would
encourage development of further private infrastructure projects
in Bangladesh,promote reforms and enable the government to
conserve limited public resources for other priorities like
education and health care.
</P>
<P>
Introduction of the 360-MW gas-fired combined-cycle power plant
into the system in June next year will help alleviate Bangladesh's
energy crunch. The total project cost is estimated at 183 million
dollars to be financed through a combination of equity and debt.
</P>
<P>
The plant is consistent with the World Bank's strategy in the
power sector for promoting reform and private-sector investment to
improve efficiency, quality and accessibility of electricity
services. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000603.0121 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Grants Aid for Bangladesh to Buy Commodities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Japan has provided around 1.17
billion taka (22 million U.S. dollars) in aid to Bangladeshi
importers,including government organizations, to import
commodities from the Organization for Economic Cooperation and
Development (OECD) and all developing countries, The Independent
newspaper reported here Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The importers would be eligible for the fund under the Japanese
Grant Aid for Debt Relief to import items of 39 categories from
these countries for non-military purposes.
</P>
<P>
An exchange of notes between the two countries was signed
recently to provide the fourth installment of the 22nd debt-relief
grant.
</P>
<P>
The Bank of Tokyo Mitsubishi Limited will be the reimbursement
bank for the import payments to the exporters.
</P>
<P>
Importers from Bangladesh will have to deposit the import value
in equivalent local currency, the taka, through their respective
dealer banks.
</P>
<P>
To utilize the fund, the importers will have to open
irrevocable letter of credits in the Japanese currency yen or
other exchangeable currencies with their respective bank branches
in the prescribed format of application.
</P>
<P>
Under the aid conditions, the imported goods can neither be
used for military purposes nor be re-exported from the country.
</P>
</TEXT>
