<HEADLINE> Pacers Make First NBA Finals in Five Attempts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Reggie Miller paced the Indiana
Pacers into the NBA Finals for the first time ever with a barrage
of Knicks-killing 3-pointers, beating New York Knicks 93-80 at
home in Game 6 of the Eastern Conference Finals.
</P>
<P>
Miller scored 34 points including five 3-pointers with four in
a span of six and half a minutes late in the game, leading the
Pacers to win the best-of-seven series 4-2.
</P>
<P>
The Pacers will take on the winners between Portland Trail
Blazers and the Los Angeles Lakers after the Lakers lost their
away game 103-93 for a 3-3 tie in the Western Conference Finals.
</P>
<P>
Miller started his shooting spree with a 3-pointer late in the
third quarter to send the game into the fourth tied at 62.
</P>
<P>
With 6:08 left, Miller made another three 3-pointers to enable
the Pacers to regain its seven-point margin, and added eight more
points on free throws the rest of the way.
</P>
<P>
This was the fifth time in seven years that the Pacers had an
opportunity to get to the finals with just one victory after lost
twice to the Knicks in 1994, once each to Orlando in 1995 and
Chicago in 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
