<HEADLINE> Trail Blazers Force Game 7 against Lakers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Steve Smith scored 26 points and Bonzi Wells had 20 with 14 in
the fourth quarter as the Trail Blazers took the lead halfway
through the first quarter and never looked back again to savor
their first home victory in the best-of-seven series.
</P>
<P>
While Kobe Bryant scored 33 points for Los Angeles, his Lakers
teammates failed to stand up dominantly with big center Shaquille
O'Neal in particular.
</P>
<P>
O'Neal, averaging 29.2 points in the playoffs, made only 17
points and 11 rebounds, and was only 7-for-17 from the field and 3-
for-10 at the line.
</P>
<P>
The Trail Blazers established their 11-point lead in the first
period and were never seriously challenged since then as O'Neal
made only eight points in the first half and missed his first six
free throws.
</P>
<P>
The Trail Blazers can become the seventh team in the NBA
history to come back from a 3-1 deficit to win a series, and the
first to do it in the West finals.
</P>
<P>
After the series tied 3-3, the deciding Game 7 will be played
in Los Angeles, where the Blazers have won two in a row.
</P>
<P>
Scottie Pippen scored a series-low nine points and was just 1-
for-6 from the field, but the deep Blazers had more than enough
offense elsewhere with five players in double figures, including
Rasheed Wallace with 18, Damon Stoudamire 14 and Arvydas Sabonis
10 points and 11 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
Glen Rice and Brian Shaw scored 12 apiece for Los Angeles.
</P>
</TEXT>
