<HEADLINE> Xinhua World Economic News Summary at 0430 GMT, June 3 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY -- The Panama Canal Authority (ACP) estimated that
the building of a third set of floodgates could cost more than
three billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
This is what ACP general secretary Leon Gonzalez said Friday
here, stating that a third set of floodgates could be an alternate
solution to the widening of the Panama Canal.
</P>
<P>
Gonzalez also said that the cost could amount to four billion
dollars if the construction of bridges, a hydroelectric plant, and
the concession are taken into account. (Panama-Canal-Cost)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MEXICO CITY -- Mexico became the second biggest trading partner
with the European Union (EU) in Latin America since it began to
implement a free trade agreement with EU last month, a report
reaching here from Belgium said.
</P>
<P>
The report said that Mexico was the 24th biggest EU trading
partner in 1998, when the European exports to Mexico amounted to 9.
3 billion U.S. dollars and imports 4 billion dollars. (Mexico-EU-
Trade)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BELGRADE -- The Yugoslav government will end years of freeze on
its citizens' foreign exchange deposit, Finance Minister Dragissa
Pessich said here Friday.
</P>
<P>
As of June 5 this year, every foreign currency depositor in the
country will be allowed to withdraw 3,000 dinar from his foreign
currency account at an exchange rate of 20 dinar against one
Deutsche mark, Pessich told reporters. (Yugoslavia-Foreign
Exchange-Freeze)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LOS ANGELES -- Worldwide sales of semiconductors reached an all
time record high of 15.2 billion U.S. dollars in April 2000, up 35.
6 percent from a year ago, an industry group said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Silicon Valley-based Semiconductor Industry Association
said the strong growth in chip revenue is being fueled by cell
phone shipments, PC demand, consumer product sales and e-commerce
over the Internet. (Chip-Market)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ATHENS -- Energy ministers from Albania, Bosnia-Herzegovina,
Bulgaria, Greece, Macedonia and Romania signed here Friday a
memorandum for the creation of a competitive regional energy
market in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
The memorandum was signed on the last day of a two-day European
Energy Conference, which aims to promote cooperation between the
European Union (EU), the Black Sea and Mediterranean countries in
major energy issues. (Balkan-Energy-Market)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NEW DELHI -- Indian Airlines (IA) Friday resumed its flight
between Calcutta and Kathmandu as an Airbus with 240 Passengers
left for Kathmandu from the N.S.C. Bose Airport in Calcutta, the
Press Trust of India said.
</P>
<P>
Special vigilance was observed at the airport for checking the
baggage of the passengers.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday the IA resumed its service between New Delhi and
Kathmandu after a five-month-long suspension of its flights to
Nepal following the hijacking of IC-814 to Kandahar. (India-Nepal-
Airlines) 
</P>
