JAKARTA, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian President Abdurrahman
Wahid is planning to hold talks with Australian Prime Minister
John Howard in Tokyo next week, Antara news agency reported
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
President Wahid said Friday in Palu, Central Sulawesi Province,
that he planned to meet with Howard on the sidelines of the
funeral of former Japanese Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi in Tokyo
next Thursday, said the report.
</P>
<P>
Wahid said one of his cabinet ministers had suggested that he
should not visit Australia yet but "I did not agree with the idea.
"
</P>
<P>
"If we wish for stability, Indonesia must have good relations
with Australia," said the president.
</P>
<P>
He said, "If there are differences between the two countries,
we should show Australia that we are a more civilian nation."
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Indonesian Foreign Minister Alwi Shihab said President
Wahid is going to pay an official visit to Australia some time
next in June.
</P>
<P>
The relations between Indonesia and Australia have been
strained since East Timor voted for independence in August last
year.
</P>
</TEXT>
