<HEADLINE> Indonesia Mulls Over Capital Control System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government is
studying the possibility of imposing capital control to arrest the
falling rupiah, the country currency, a senior official said.
</P>
<P>
"Frankly speaking, Indonesia's foreign exchange regime is so
liberal that we need to make some necessary adjustments," local
leading newspapers Saturday quoted Trade and Industry Minister
Luhut Pandjaitan as saying.
</P>
<P>
The risk of applying capital control would be less than letting
the currency fluctuate freely like it is now, the minister said
Friday on the sidelines of a seminar when commenting on a
statement made by Horst Koehler, new managing director of the
International Monetary Fund (IMF), earlier in Bangkok.
</P>
<P>
Koehler had said capital control was not a taboo.
</P>
<P>
Pandjaitan said the government's main objective in controlling
the flow of currencies is to stabilize the rupiah and prevent the
currency from being used for speculative trading.
</P>
<P>
Amid heightened talks of the possibility that Indonesia would
impose currency control, the rupiah gained ground Friday while
stock prices fell another 2.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
Foreign exchange dealers said speculation that the government
would impose currency control helped boost the rupiah to close
higher at 8,385 to the U.S. dollar from 8,630 Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Jakarta Stock Exchange hit another one-year low Friday,
ending down by 2.2 percent, or 9.87 points at 444.44 due to
worries over currency control.
</P>
<P>
However, Bank Indonesia (central bank) Governor Sjahril Sabirin
expressed opposition to "all-out" capital controls, but said he
would consider some measures to control the flow of foreign
exchange in and out of the country and ensure stability in the
currency's value. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
