<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan Troops, Rebels Exchange Mortar Fire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lankan government troops and
Tamil rebels exchanged mortar fire Friday in the northern Jaffna
Peninsula,the official Daily News reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted military sources as saying Tamil rebels
ferociously fired mortars at army defenses in the Chavakachcheri
area of the peninsula and government troops retaliated.
</P>
<P>
At least 15 Tamil rebels were killed by army patrols at four
different locations around the Chavakachcheri Friday, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
Fighting has eased on the Jaffna Peninsula after a few weeks'
fierce battles. The Tamil rebels, who have been fighting for a
separate Tamil state in the north and east of the country since
1983, are trying to recapture the peninsula, their former
stronghold which they lost to the government troops in May 1996.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, around 10,000 civilians in parts of Batticaloa
district, who were forcibly evacuated by the rebels a few days ago,
have begun returning to their homes, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The rebels forced the civilians out of their homes in order to
attack the troops' Vavunathivu camp close to Batticaloa town, the
report said, adding that however, the rebels failed to achieve
their aim as the troops stood their ground courageously despite
mortar fire.
</P>
</TEXT>
