<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yugoslavia to End Freeze on Foreign Exchange Savings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, June 2 (Xinhua) -- The Yugoslav government will end
years of freeze on its citizens' foreign exchange deposit, Finance
Minister Dragissa Pessich said here Friday.
</P>
<P>
As of June 5 this year, every foreign currency depositor in the
country will be allowed to withdraw 3,000 dinar from his foreign
currency account at an exchange rate of 20 dinar against one
Deutsche mark, Pessich told reporters.
</P>
<P>
And as from July 1, the depositors can each withdraw 150 marks
in foreign exchange, he added.
</P>
<P>
The official foreign exchange rate in Yugoslavia is six dinar
against one mark.
</P>
<P>
The amount of foreign exchange frozen by the government stands
at 7.4 billion marks, of which 180 million marks will be paid to
depositors this year, said the finance minister.
</P>
<P>
In the early 1990s, the Yugoslav government froze all its
citizens' foreign exchange accounts in the country's commercial
banks, following the disintegration of the former Yugoslavia and
international sanctions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
