<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia to Buy Warships from South Korea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian Navy chief said the
country plans to buy three personnel carrier ships from South
Korea.
</P>
<P>
"For the time being we will only buy one but we may need three
in the near future," Navy Chief of Staff Admiral Achmad Sutjipto
said while observing an exercise by trainers in South Malang, East
Java, on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Sutjipto said he is dissatisfied with warships of the Landing
Ship Tank (LST) type in the navy's possession because their
specifications are not good enough for combat-ready troops.
</P>
<P>
"Our soldiers are now transported with old LST ships. Because
of the ships' inadequate features, they easily get tired by just
traveling in them. Therefore, we will replace them with more
comfortable and quicker ships," he was quoted by the Antara News
Agency Saturday as saying.
</P>
<P>
Sutjipto said the government welcomes the navy's idea to
replace the LSTs and the navy is now waiting for the required
budgetary allocation.
</P>
<P>
The navy chief disclosed that the United States has renewed an
offer of cooperation in a joint naval war game between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
The United States froze military ties with Indonesia eight
months ago after hundreds of people were killed in East Timor
after the area voted for independence from Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
"America made the offer and we accepted it. The joint exercise
is scheduled for July," Sutjipto said.
</P>
<P>
In the joint exercise the U.S. Navy will send units from the
Seventh Fleet and its Marine Corps in the Pacific while Indonesia
will dispatch commando units from the Maritime Fleet and units of
the Marine Corps. During the joint exercise the two sides will
conduct a comparative study of each other's powers and potentials
to produce a reliable amphibious force for combat.
</P>
<P>
"The naval personnel to be involved in the joint exercise may
amount to one battalion," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
