<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weekly Review of Health News in China (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Following are the highlights of
major news on health care and medical research in China over the
past week:
</P>
<P>
China to Set Action Plan for Tobacco Control
</P>
<P>
Public health authorities in China are considering a national
plan of action for tobacco control to tackle the prevailing
problems of smoking.
</P>
<P>
Sixty-three percent of male adults and four percent of females,
or 320 million people, are smokers in China, making the country
the world's biggest consumer of tobacco products.
</P>
<P>
Survey Finds 20 Percent of Middle School Students Smoke
</P>
<P>
A worldwide survey shows that more than 20 percent of students
in China's junior high schools have tried smoking. Many of them
may become habitual smokers in the future.
</P>
<P>
Out of some 12,000 students aged between 13 and 15, 32.5
percent of boys and 13 percent of girls have tried to take up the
habit. The average smoking rate is 22.5 percent, and the average
age of taking the first puff is 10 years of age.
</P>
<P>
Study Shows Smoking Causes Heavy Costs in China
</P>
<P>
Tobacco-related deaths, loss of laborers and medical
expenditure have led to heavy social and economic costs to China,
the world's biggest tobacco producer and consumer.
</P>
<P>
Smoking was responsible for 514,000 deaths, while causing the
loss of 1.14 million laborers and bringing about 22.9 billion yuan
(2.7 billion U.S. dollars) in direct medical fees in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Ministry Denies Rumors of Mainland Bird Flu
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Agriculture denied Monday the rumors in the
Hong Kong and Taiwan Media that high pathogenic avian influenza (
HPAI) has broken out in the Chinese mainland's Shanghai, and
Guangdong and Shandong provinces.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Zhongqiu, deputy director of the ministry 's Bureau of
Animal Production and Health, said that the mainland has
maintained a tight grip on the prevention of all kinds of animal
and poultry diseases, particularly the HPAI (bird flu) listed as a
Class A infection by the Ministry of Agriculture.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
