<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weekly Review of Health News in China (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Chinese Doctors Restore Nerve-Damaged Hand
</P>
<P>
Long Yuhe, 46, recently received near-deadly electric shocks to
both arms and hands. The nerves in his left wrist and hand were
totally destroyed, while those in his right hand and arm were
dying.
</P>
<P>
In an eight-hour operation, doctors at Tianxi Hospital of the
Anshan Iron and Steel Group in Anshan city repaired the nerves in
three fingers of Long's right hand and saved the limb. But his
left arm had to be amputated.
</P>
<P>
China To Hold Seminar On Pharmaceutical Sector
</P>
<P>
A seminar on the development strategy for China's
pharmaceutical industry in the 21st century will be held on June
14 in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The seminar will focus on possible measures for medicine
enterprises that may become necessary after China enters the World
Trade Organization (WTO).
</P>
<P>
International Cooperation Helps Improve Children's Health
</P>
<P>
China, with about 370 million people under the age of 17, has
significantly increased international cooperation to improve
children's health care over the past decades.
</P>
<P>
The country has jointly established a great number of child
health organizations with overseas hospitals, universities,
research institutes, and government departments, including the
Child Health Research Center, the Canada-China Child Health
Foundation, and 74 children-friendly centers.
</P>
<P>
Dental Health In China a Concern
</P>
<P>
A recent national survey showed that in China, 76.55 percent of
the five-year-olds have had decayed teeth, at an average of four
each.
</P>
<P>
The incidence of dental problems among teenagers is also
serious, with 85 percent of middle school students suffering from
periodontal difficulties. The survey also found that one-third of
all Chinese still do not have the habit of regularly brushing
their teeth. 
</P>
</TEXT>
