<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0025 GMT, June 3 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON -- Britain said Friday that Fiji might be suspended from
the Commonwealth if its new rulers do not return the country to
democratic constitutional government.
</P>
<P>
John Battle, a Foreign Office minister of state, said
suspension was a real option when Commonwealth foreign ministers
meet in London next week to discuss the crisis in Fiji.
</P>
<P>
But he said it was too early yet to make a decision. (Britain-
Fiji-Commonwealth)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LAGOS -- The U.N. mission in Sierra Leone has launched an
investigation into human rights abuses by the country's fighting
parties, an official of the mission said Friday in the country's
capital Freetown.
</P>
<P>
Reports reaching here quoted Richard Bernett, head of the
mission's human rights section as saying that the probe is
intended to get a "complete picture" of the human rights situation
in the war-torn west African nation.
</P>
<P>
He said human rights investigations have been undertaken in
places in the country like Freetown, Waterloo, Masiaka, Port Loko,
Lungi Bo and Rogbere junction for over three weeks. (UN-SLeone)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CAMP ZEIST, the Netherlands -- A British researcher Friday
backed the prosecution's case against two Libyans by testifying
that the bomb that brought down Pan Am Flight 103 was some way
away from the fuselage skin.
</P>
<P>
Christopher Peel, from the British Defense Evaluation and
Research Agency, calculated that a 450-gram explosive device was
hidden 24 inches (60.9 centimeters) from the aircraft wall.
</P>
<P>
His calculation had a margin of error of four inches (10
centimeters) either way, he added. (The Netherlands-Lockerbie)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- China Friday demanded a probe into "the
possible severe violation" of the humanitarian law by NATO in its
bombing of Yugoslavia, saying that convinced evidence is needed to
support the allegation that there was no basis for a U.N.
investigation into the unilateral NATO air strikes.
</P>
<P>
Chen Xu, representative of the Chinese Mission to the United
Nations, told an open Security Council meeting that China fully
supports such an investigation by the International Criminal
Tribunal for the Former Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
"It is our hope that the tribunal can implement the law in
objective and justice way, not to become a political tool," he
said. (China-NATO-Bombing) 
</P>
</TEXT>
