<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Keegan's Challenge for In-form Barmby </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 2 (Xinhua) -- England soccer team manager Kevin
Keegan has thrown down the gauntlet to Nick Barmby and challenged
him to stake a claim for a place in his Euro 2000 starting line-up.
</P>
<P>
Barmby will start his first international for nearly four years
when he plays in England's final warm-up match against Malta in
Valletta on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The Everton midfielder has been allocated the left-sided role
in a 4-4-2 system and Keegan insisted that position was still up
for grabs ahead of the Euro opener with Portugal on June 12 in
Eindhoven.
</P>
<P>
It is a remarkable and rapid rise for Barmby with Keegan
admitting that he was not even in his plans for the summer a few
weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
But Barmby came from the back of the queue to oust Peter
Beardsley from the Euro '96 squad after scoring twice against
China.
</P>
<P>
He also had the distinction of scoring the first goal of Glenn
Hoddle's reign in a World Cup qualifier in Moldova in September
1996.
</P>
<P>
But that was his last England appearance until the former
Tottenham player made a huge impression on Keegan with his
performance in the final third of Wednesday's win over the Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
Now another impressive performance on Saturday, against
admittedly less quality opposition, could seal his spot in what
remains the problem area for Keegan.
</P>
<P>
It also suggests that Keegan remains to be convinced that Steve
McManaman is the answer to his prayers in the left-sided berth -
which is where he will have to be accommodated if not given a free
role as against Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
Keegan said: "I think Nick Barmby thoroughly deserves his
chance. If you had asked me a month ago, I don't think I would
have thought that would be possible. I have said to him to give me
90 minutes against Malta in the same vein as the 30 when he was on
the pitch against the Ukraine - and I think the 4-4-2 system will
suit him."
</P>
<P>
"He really expressed himself well the other night and when he
came on he picked up the pace of the game from the first second.
He looked like he was a player on a mission. Nick Barmby came
through to make the squad for Euro 96 - but he's in the squad now
and what all the players are thinking about is making the side for
the first game against Portugal," he said.
</P>
<P>
Third choice keeper Richard Wright will cap a memorable week by
winning his first cap to follow on from helping Ipswich reach the
Premiership, via their play-off final victory over Barnsley on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Sunderland striker Kevin Phillips will also get his first start
for seven months - just three days after fearing he would not make
the final 22.
</P>
<P>
Phillips was last in the first X1 on his home ground at the
Stadium Of Light for the friendly international with Belgium.
Chelsea skipper Dennis Wise will get another chance to stake a
claim for a central midfield role after playing on the left
against Brazil last weekend.
</P>
<P>
Keegan said he would make several changes during the game but
he insisted: "I will not make a farce of it. There are things I
would like to look at but the real message is 'let's keep up the
good work'." 
</P>
</TEXT>
