<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Science News: Weekly Highlights (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Following are the highlights of
major science stories released by Xinhua this week:
</P>
<P>
China Hosts Int'l Meeting on Avian Paleontology
</P>
<P>
The Fifth International Meeting of the Society of Avian
Paleontology and Evolution and the Symposium on Jehol Biota
started on June 1 in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
At the four-day meeting, organized by the Chinese Academy of
Sciences (CAS) Institute of Vertebrate Paleontology and
Paleoanthropology (IVPP), 70 foreign and 80 Chinese
paleontologists are to discuss the hottest issues in paleontology.
</P>
<P>
China Drafts Plan for Dust Storm Prevention
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Science and Technology has drafted a plan for
prevention of dust storms and desertification in China to be
implemented in the following five years.
</P>
<P>
An official with the Ministry of Science and Technology said
the plan will be executed starting from 2001.
</P>
<P>
According to the plan, in the capital city of Beijing and
neighboring cities of Tianjin, Zhangjiakou and Chengde, more trees
and grass will be planted in both urban and suburban areas and
high-efficient agriculture will be encouraged.
</P>
<P>
Exhibition of Popular Science Opens in Beijing
</P>
<P>
A popular science exhibition, which puts on show the history of
Nobel Prize and its winners, opened in Beijing on May 27.
</P>
<P>
Sponsored by the Chinese Academy of Sciences (CAS), the
Publicity Department of CPC Central Committee, China Association
for Science and Technology, the Ministry of Science and Technology
and other organizations, the exhibition is aimed to improve people
's awareness of science and eliminate the negative influence of
pseudo-science.
</P>
<P>
The exhibition offers a brief history of scientific development
over the past 100 years and will invite renowned experts and
scholars to give speeches on popular science topics.
</P>
<P>
Scientists Recommend 100 Popular Science Books
</P>
<P>
Chinese scientists have come out with a Top-100 list of Chinese
and foreign popular science books published over the past 20 years.
</P>
<P>
The books include 63 Chinese and 37 foreign works and were
chosen through a project, sponsored by the Chinese Academy of
Sciences, the Ministry of Science and Technology, and the Chinese
Association for Science and Technology.
</P>
<P>
The recommendation of 100 popular science books is a follow-up
of a similar activity last year, in which scientists recommended
93 superior books of the same category published in the 20th
Century.
</P>
</TEXT>
