<DOCNO> XIE20000603.0162 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brazil, Argentina, Chile Oppose Sanctions Against Peru </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Brazilian President Fernando
Henrique Cardoso, his Argentine counterpart, Fernando de la Rua,
and Chilean President Ricardo Lagos decided to adopt a common
position of acceptance of the result of the Peruvian elections in
the Organization of American States (OAS) General Assembly that
starts Sunday in Windsor, Canada.
</P>
<P>
Local press reports Saturday said that the decision was taken
by the presidents Friday in Berlin, where they were attending a
meeting of 14 heads of state on the so-called "Third Way."
</P>
<P>
The Brazilian president said after a dinner with his Argentine
and Chilean counterparts that the three countries concur that no
retaliation should be exerted against Peru.
</P>
<P>
Cardoso said that what occurred in Peru was not a coup, but a
legitimate election. "It was the Peruvian people who decided," he
said.
</P>
<P>
According to Cardoso, the three leaders underscored during the
dinner that they do not want to interfere in the internal affairs
of other countries, although they consider that there is a general
need of affirming democracy in the continent.
</P>
<P>
The United States was unsuccessful in its attempt to have
sanctions against Peru approved in the OAS Permanent Council
special meeting held Wednesday in Washington because of the strong
opposition of Brazil.
</P>
<P>
The United States will probably present again during the next
OAS yearly General Assembly a proposal to impose sanction upon
Peru under the pretext of defending democracy in the continent.
</P>
<P>
The local press reports said that the stance of Paraguay,
Uruguay, and Ecuador is similar to that of Brazil, which
recognizes the Peruvian electoral process and affirms that the
election was made according to internal legislation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
