<HEADLINE> Britain to Pull More Troops From N.Ireland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Britain will withdraw about 500
soldiers from Northern Ireland due to improving security, thus
reducing its troop levels in Northern Ireland to their lowest
point since 1970.
</P>
<P>
Northern Ireland's police head Ronnie Flanagan announced
Saturday that a battalion of troops based in middle Northern
Ireland are to return to England as part of an overall
demilitarization program. The soldiers will return home in two
weeks' time when their current six-month tour of Northern Ireland
ends.
</P>
<P>
The withdrawal will take the number of soldiers stationed in
Northern Ireland to below 13,500.
</P>
<P>
Flanagan said the further reduction in troop levels was "
appropriate" even though there was still a security threat from
dissidents.
</P>
<P>
The decision to start scaling down the British Army presence in
Northern Ireland was taken following the IRA's offer to put its
arms "beyond use" on May 6.
</P>
<P>
The announcement of further troop reductions followed the start
of work to dismantle two army observation posts in the Roman
Catholic areas of Belfast.
</P>
<P>
Preliminary work to dismantle army bases in Cookstown in County
Tyrone and at Cloghogue in south Armagh has also begun.
</P>
<P>
The scaling down of the army presence in Northern Ireland has
come as a result of a security assessment which indicated a
reduced threat from terrorism.
</P>
<P>
The British government has said it hopes to take "substantial
measures" to normalize security arrangements by June 2001, the new
deadline by which both London and Dublin aim to secure full
implementation of the 1998 Good Friday Agreement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
