<HEADLINE> OAS Cannot Apply Sanctions to Peru: Analyst </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LIMA, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The Organization of American States (
OAS) has no faculties to deny the elections or to apply economic
sanctions to Peru, political analyst Enrique Bernales said
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The specialist's statements were made on the eve of the OAS
General Assembly to be held Sunday in Canada, where the American
foreign ministers will discuss the Peruvian political crisis
unleashed after the second-round election held Sunday, May 28.
</P>
<P>
Peruvian Foreign Minister Fernando de Trazegnies will face
during the OAS meeting the accusations of electoral fraud that the
Peruvian political opposition is presenting before the
international community.
</P>
<P>
"The worst sanction the multilateral organization can impose is
to suspend the membership to a country that had interrupted with
violence the juridical and democratic principles in the region,"
said Bernal.
</P>
<P>
Bernal explained that Article 9 of the OAS Charter establishes
the suspension of a member country when a nation interrupts the
democratic continuity and the juridical principles of the
interamerican organization.
</P>
<P>
This process is very long and exhausts all the possibilities
before applying the maximum punishment, as it happened with Cuba,
whose government was excluded from participating in the OAS by a
resolution of the Eighth Consultation Meeting of the Foreign
Ministers in 1962.
</P>
<P>
The analyst said that in the Peruvian case, the OAS must soften
the two sectors in conflict so they can sit down to negotiate a
solution and establish a commitment of governability for the
country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000603.0170 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethiopia Not to Withdraw from Eritrea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopia will redeploy its
troops to May 6, 1998 positions only when international
peacekeeping force set foot at the high grounds in Eritrea now
under the control of Ethiopian army, Prime Minister Meles Zenawi
said here Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia will not allow its victory at the warfront to be
affected by the ongoing proximity talks in Algiers, Algeria,
Meles told reporters.
</P>
<P>
He said although Ethiopia does not have any intention to annex
the Eritrean sovereign territories, it will not withdraw its
forces without reliable security guarantee from the international
community.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia has proposed the Algiers proximity talks organizers
that Eritrea sign an agreement that it would not again initiate a
war against Ethiopia, and the high grounds that will be evacuated
by Ethiopian troops be controlled by international peacekeeping
forces, Meles said.
</P>
<P>
The proximity talks between Ethiopia and Eritrea, that has been
going on since Tuesday, is under the auspices of Chairman of the
Organization of African Unity (OAU), Algerian President Abdelaziz
Bouteflika.
</P>
<P>
If the international community cannot deploy a peacekeeping
force on those grounds due to financial and manpower constraints,
Ethiopia is ready to shoulder the responsibility of ensuring
peace in the area, he said.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister said that the restoration of the status quo
ante, which has been the core element of the OAU Framework
Agreement and the Modalities, is irrelevant currently as it has
been successfully accomplished militarily.
</P>
<P>
Those points of the peace documents that deal with border
demarcation and other related issues should review in accordance
with the existing situation on the ground, he noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
