<HEADLINE> Electoral Authorities Elected in Venezuela </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Venezuela's National Legislative
Commission (CLN) or minicongress of Venezuela elected Saturday the
new members of the National Electoral Council (CNE) prior to the
upcoming general elections in the country.
</P>
<P>
The new CNE direction will substitute for the one that resigned
after the suspension of the elections scheduled for May 28, and in
which the presidency, 23 department governorships and 335
municipality mayoralties will be elected.
</P>
<P>
The persons appointed title holders and stand-ins for the top
electoral organization came from among 23 candidates proposed by
political parties' representatives, the business sector, and
independent organizations.
</P>
<P>
CLN President Luis Miquilena said that the persons elected to
the CNE will assume their posts next Monday and will decide the
new date for the elections.
</P>
<P>
The representative of the non-government organization "We Want
Elections," Elias Santana, said that technical, professional
aspects prevailed in the selection over and above any other aspect.
</P>
<P>
The suspension of the Venezuelan elections agreed on last May
25 by technical breakdowns unleashed a strong internal controversy
in the country that forced the CNE board to resigned on May 30.
</P>
<P>
Under the rewritten constitution approved in a December
referendum, Venezuelans were due to vote on May 28 for a president
-- with incumbent President Hugo Chavez and his challenger
Francisco Arias as candidates -- a new National Assembly, state
governors, mayors, councilors, parish and regional legislative
councils. 
</P>
</TEXT>
