<HEADLINE> U.S. Congress Delegation Visits Santiago de Cuba </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, June 3 (Xinhua) -- A U.S. Congressmen Black Caucus
delegation which arrived in Havana Wednesday went to Santiago de
Cuba Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The 17-member delegation is headed by Democrat House
Representative James Clyburn of South Carolina, and includes
Democrats Bennie Gordon of Mississippi, Gregory Meeks of New York,
as well as lawmakers' assistants, journalists and community
leaders.
</P>
<P>
The legislators, who oversee the reality of the island, are
accompanied by Pastors for Peace solidarity movement leader Lucius
Walker and Helen Bernstein, a member of that organization.
</P>
<P>
The Radio National Newscast said that the visitors laid a
wreath on the grave of the Santa Ifigenia cemetery in Santiago de
Cuba, where national hero Jose Marti is buried.
</P>
<P>
Clyburn told the local press that the United States Congress
will start next week the discussions on the changes or lifting of
the embargo to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
The delegates support the lifting of the embargo to the sale of
U.S. medicines and food to the island, in order to lay foundations
for the complete cessation of the embargo in a not very far future,
said Clyburn.
</P>
<P>
He added that the members of the visiting group are very
interested in the trips of exchange between Cuba and the United
States "because we are well aware of the similarities of our
history and our past."
</P>
<P>
The mission has met during its visit to the island with Cuban
Parliament President Ricardo Alarcon, Foreign Minister Felipe
Perez Roque, Economy and Planning Minister Jose Luis Rodriguez,
and Culture Minister Abel Prieto.
</P>
<P>
The presence in Havana of the U.S. Congress Black Caucus
members happened at the time of the visit of Senator Blanche
Lincoln and Representative Marion Berry, members of the Democrat
caucus for Arkansas, who led a delegation of agriculture
businessmen.
</P>
<P>
Craigh Johnstone, U.S. Chamber of Commerce vice chairman, was
also this week in the island promoting the strengthening of
bilateral cooperation established in 1999 between that
organization and the Cuban government.
</P>
<P>
U.S. business interests are pushing Congress to dismantle or
substantially weaken the embargo erected by U.S. President John F.
Kennedy in 1962 and to lift the remaining restrictions on American
food and medicines sales, said analysts.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. House of Representatives will vote later this month
on a provision in an agricultural bill to license U.S. sales of
food and medicine to Cuba as long as they aren't subsidized by U.S.
taxpayers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
